      "role": "user",
      "content": "I'm not sure i follow the wizard and imp stuff lol. can you just explain specifically what happens if the seller doesn't fulfill their end of the deal once the money is in escrow?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries, I won't hold it against you for not being enchanted by the wizard and imp analogy. Let me break it down for you in simpler terms.\n\nIf the seller doesn't fulfill their end of the deal, the escrow account can be used to hold the funds until the issue is resolved. Think of it like a \"goblin's hold\" on the funds – the escrow account is like a magical barrier that prevents the funds from being released until the seller has completed their obligations.\n\nFor example, if the seller fails to transfer the ownership of the property, the escrow account can be used to hold the funds until the property is transferred to your name. The escrow agent will then release the funds to the seller once the property is transferred, and the issue is resolved.\n\nIn some cases, the escrow account can also be used to hold funds for repairs or credits that are owed to the buyer. It's like a \"goblin's stash\" – the escrow account is holding onto the funds until the seller has fulfilled their obligations, and then releases them to the buyer.\n\nAs for what happens if the seller doesn't fulfill their end of the deal, the buyer can usually request that the escrow account be used to",
